{
  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B2_171_perfect_tenses_overview",
  "title": "B2.171 Perfect Tenses Overview — The Grammar of Reflection",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we use 'have' to connect the past with the present: 'I have seen it,' 'She has finished,' 'They had gone.' Spanish does the same with **haber + past participle**—but it uses the perfect tenses more consciously to show how actions ripple through time. English does this by feeling; Spanish does it by structure, marking whether something happened recently, long ago, or before another past moment. It’s the grammar of memory—of what still echoes after it’s done."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ The Formula:**\nAll perfect tenses use *haber* + past participle. The participle never changes form—it always ends in *-ado* (for -ar verbs) or *-ido* (for -er/-ir verbs): *hablado, comido, vivido.*\n\n**2️⃣ Main Perfect Tenses:**\n| Tense | Structure | Example | Meaning |\n|-------|------------|----------|----------|\n| **Present Perfect** | *he, has, ha, hemos, habéis, han + participle* | *He visto la película.* | I’ve seen the movie (recent past with present link). |\n| **Past Perfect (Pluperfect)** | *había, habías, había, habíamos, habíais, habían + participle* | *Había comido antes de salir.* | I had eaten before leaving (past before past). |\n| **Future Perfect** | *habré, habrás, habrá, habremos, habréis, habrán + participle* | *Habré terminado para entonces.* | I will have finished by then (action expected by a future time). |\n| **Conditional Perfect** | *habría, habrías, habría, habríamos, habríais, habrían + participle* | *Habría ido si pudiera.* | I would have gone if I could (unreal past). |\n\n**3️⃣ How it works:**\nThe auxiliary *haber* changes to mark the time frame; the participle marks the action itself. *He visto* looks backward from now; *había visto* looks backward from another point in the past; *habré visto* imagines looking back from the future.\n\n**4️⃣ Agreement note:**\nUnlike *ser* or *estar,* participles after *haber* never change for gender or number: *ellas han comido* (not *comidas*). The event, not the doer, is what counts.\n\n**5️⃣ Shortcut summary:**\n| When to Use | Time View |\n|-------------|------------|\n| *He hablado* | Recent, still relevant |\n| *Había hablado* | Earlier than another past moment |\n| *Habré hablado* | Expected completion in the future |\n| *Habría hablado* | Missed or hypothetical past |\nSpanish builds emotional time lines by bending *haber* through memory."
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "From Latin’s auxiliary *habere* ('to have, to hold'), Spanish turned ownership into temporality—what we 'have done' becomes what we carry forward in memory.",
      "story": "Perfect tenses in Spanish are verbs turned inward—they measure not when something happened, but how it still lives in the present mind. *He amado* ('I have loved') doesn’t describe a fact; it confesses endurance. *Había amado* pulls the thread deeper, remembering love before it faded.\n\nSpanish perfect tenses move through time like ripples. The present perfect (*he hecho*) feels close, warm, unfinished. The pluperfect (*había hecho*) belongs to stories told by firelight—what was already over when something else began. The future perfect (*habré hecho*) imagines completion before arrival; the conditional perfect (*habría hecho*) mourns the chance that never came.\n\nEvery use of *haber* carries weight. It’s a ledger of experience, not just grammar. The verb’s rhythm reminds speakers that time is cumulative. Even when moments pass, Spanish grammar keeps them accountable—each action stored as something still owned by memory.",
      "wrap_line": "Spanish perfect tenses remind us that the past never disappears—it becomes part of what we have, what we hold, and what we are."
    },
