  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B2_172_present_perfect_vs_preterite",
  "title": "B2.172 Present Perfect vs. Preterite — Experience vs. Event",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we say 'I’ve eaten' or 'I ate,' often using them interchangeably. But Spanish draws a sharper line between the two. The **present perfect** (*he comido*) connects a past action to the present—it still feels relevant. The **preterite** (*comí*) marks a completed event, sealed in the past. English does this by tone and context; Spanish does it through grammar, deciding whether the past still echoes or has already closed."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ Structure:**\nBoth use *haber + past participle* or a simple past form, but they serve different timelines.\n\n| Tense | Formula | Example | Meaning |\n|-------|----------|----------|----------|\n| Present Perfect | *he, has, ha, hemos, habéis, han + participle* | *He comido.* | I’ve eaten (recent, still relevant). |\n| Preterite | *comí, comiste, comió, comimos, comisteis, comieron* | *Comí.* | I ate (finished, detached from now). |\n\n**2️⃣ Core Difference:**\nThe **present perfect** describes actions affecting or continuing into the present.\n- *He leído ese libro.* (I’ve read that book → I know it now.)\n- *¿Has visto a Marta hoy?* (Have you seen Marta today? → 'Today' is not over yet.)\n\nThe **preterite** describes actions completed in a finished time frame.\n- *Leí ese libro el año pasado.* (I read that book last year → finished period.)\n- *Vi a Marta ayer.* (I saw Marta yesterday → closed moment.)\n\n**3️⃣ Regional variation:**\nIn Spain, the **present perfect** often replaces the preterite for recent actions:\n- *He comido hace poco.* (I ate recently.)\nIn Latin America, speakers prefer the **preterite** for almost all completed events:\n- *Comí hace poco.* (Same meaning, but grammatically preterite.)\n\n**4️⃣ Quick guide:**\n| Meaning Type | Choose | Example |\n|---------------|---------|----------|\n| Ongoing / relevant now | Present perfect | *He perdido mis llaves.* (I’ve lost my keys.) |\n| Completed / past moment | Preterite | *Perdí mis llaves ayer.* (I lost my keys yesterday.) |\n\n**5️⃣ Tip:**\nIf time feels open → *he hecho.* If it feels closed → *hice.* Spanish uses tense to measure connection, not just chronology."
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "From Latin perfect systems, Spanish inherited both 'present relevance' and 'completed past' forms, preserving the emotional link between action and memory.",
      "story": "The difference between *he hecho* and *hice* lies in how Spanish treats memory. The present perfect holds the past like a photo in your hand—it’s recent, meaningful, still alive. The preterite stores it in an album—it happened, but the moment has passed.\n\nThis distinction reflects how Spanish perceives time as layered, not linear. *He vivido muchas cosas* is experience remembered with warmth—it continues to shape you. *Viví muchas cosas* is recollection, a chapter already turned. The grammar doesn’t just locate time; it measures closeness of feeling.\n\nIn everyday conversation, these tenses paint tone. A Spanish speaker might say *he tenido un día difícil* to invite empathy—the day isn’t done yet. But *tuve un día difícil* closes the door; it belongs to the past. Writers use this contrast to move characters through reflection and resolution. Each choice bends time through emotion.",
      "wrap_line": "In Spanish, grammar carries distance—*he visto* remembers, *vi* recalls. One reaches back; the other leaves it there."
    },
