  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B2_174_future_perfect",
  "title": "B2.174 Future Perfect — Anticipating Completion",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we use 'will have' to imagine something completed in the future: 'By tomorrow, I will have finished,' 'She will have arrived by noon.' Spanish expresses the same idea with the **future perfect**, built from *haber* in the future + a past participle: *habré terminado, habrás llegado, habrán comido.* English does this by predicting completion through 'will have'; Spanish does it by imagining the future as already remembered—a tense that looks forward and backward at once."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ Structure:**\nFormula: *haber (future) + past participle.*\n| Subject | Haber (future) | Example (estudiar) |\n|----------|----------------|--------------------|\n| yo | habré | habré estudiado |\n| tú | habrás | habrás estudiado |\n| él/ella/usted | habrá | habrá estudiado |\n| nosotros | habremos | habremos estudiado |\n| vosotros | habréis | habréis estudiado |\n| ellos/ustedes | habrán | habrán estudiado |\n\n**2️⃣ Core uses:**\n1. **Completion before a future point in time:**\n   - *Para las diez, ya habré terminado el trabajo.* (By ten, I’ll have finished the work.)\n2. **Assumption or probability about a past event:**\n   - *Habrá llegado tarde.* (He’s probably arrived late.)\n   - *¿Dónde estará Juan? Habrá salido.* (Where’s Juan? He must’ve gone out.)\n\n**3️⃣ Time markers:**\n*para, dentro de, antes de, cuando, ya, todavía no.*\n- *Dentro de un año, habremos aprendido mucho.* (Within a year, we’ll have learned a lot.)\n- *Para entonces, ya habrán llegado.* (By then, they’ll have already arrived.)\n\n**4️⃣ Comparison with other tenses:**\n| Tense | Function | Example |\n|--------|-----------|----------|\n| Future Simple | Event that will happen | *Llegaré mañana.* (I’ll arrive tomorrow.) |\n| Future Perfect | Event that will be completed before another future moment | *Habré llegado para mañana.* (I’ll have arrived by tomorrow.) |\n\n**5️⃣ Tip:**\nThe future perfect is not only prediction—it’s reflection. Spanish uses it to imagine completed outcomes, both logical and emotional. The structure looks ahead, but the feeling belongs to hindsight."
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "From Latin’s 'futurum exactum,' this tense carried forward the notion of an action completed before a defined point in the future.",
      "story": "The future perfect is Spanish’s most philosophical tense. It speaks from the future as if looking back, allowing speakers to live inside a moment that hasn’t yet arrived. When someone says *habré terminado*, they’re not only forecasting success—they’re rehearsing relief.\n\nSpanish uses this tense to express both expectation and reflection. It’s how you talk about what will one day be memory. *Dentro de cinco años, habremos cambiado mucho* doesn’t just mark time—it anticipates transformation. The verb *haber* here means 'to have' in its purest sense: to hold something complete in the future’s hands.\n\nThis tense also lets Spanish express gentle speculation about the past: *¿Habrá llegado ya?* (Has he probably arrived by now?). It’s a guess softened by grammar, proof that Spanish prefers wonder to certainty. The future perfect is not just prediction—it’s contemplation, a grammatical way of imagining fulfillment.\n\nIn writing, it often closes circles of thought. It’s used by planners, poets, and dreamers alike: those who picture what will have been and find comfort in that imagined conclusion.",
      "wrap_line": "The future perfect looks ahead with memory in its eyes—grammar that predicts not only what will happen, but how it will feel to have arrived there."
