  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B2_175_conditional_perfect",
  "title": "B2.175 Conditional Perfect — The Grammar of Hypothetical Past",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we say 'would have done' to describe something that didn’t happen but could have: 'I would have gone,' 'She would have called,' 'They would have helped.' Spanish expresses this with the **conditional perfect**, made from *haber* in the conditional + a past participle: *habría ido, habrías llamado, habrían ayudado.* English does this by layering condition on top of the past; Spanish does it by bending time completely—imagining a past that never was, but might have been."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ Structure:**\nFormula: *haber (conditional) + past participle.*\n| Subject | Haber (conditional) | Example (hacer) |\n|----------|---------------------|------------------|\n| yo | habría | habría hecho |\n| tú | habrías | habrías hecho |\n| él/ella/usted | habría | habría hecho |\n| nosotros | habríamos | habríamos hecho |\n| vosotros | habríais | habríais hecho |\n| ellos/ustedes | habrían | habrían hecho |\n\n**2️⃣ Main Uses:**\n1. **Hypothetical past events:** what would have happened if something else had been different.\n   - *Si hubiera tenido tiempo, habría ido contigo.* (If I had had time, I would have gone with you.)\n2. **Regret or reflection:** expressing what one wishes had been done.\n   - *Habría estudiado más si lo hubiera sabido.* (I would have studied more if I’d known.)\n3. **Polite speculation:** soft guesses about past events.\n   - *Habría llegado tarde.* (He must have arrived late.)\n\n**3️⃣ Relationship with the pluperfect subjunctive:**\nConditional perfect and pluperfect subjunctive often appear together in “if” clauses:\n- *Si hubiera sabido, habría venido.* (If I had known, I would have come.)\n→ *hubiera sabido* = impossible condition, *habría venido* = imagined outcome.\n\n**4️⃣ Quick Contrast:**\n| Meaning | English | Spanish Example |\n|----------|----------|------------------|\n| Hypothetical past | would have done | *habría hecho* |\n| Actual past | did | *hizo* |\n| Present condition | would do | *haría* |\n\n**5️⃣ Summary Tip:**\nUse the **conditional perfect** when your mind looks backward but still wonders, “What if?” Spanish captures that alternate history not with sadness, but with precision—grammar for memory’s imagination."
    },
