  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B2_176_subjunctive_present_perfect",
  "title": "B2.176 Subjunctive Present Perfect — Doubt Meets Memory",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we sometimes express hope, doubt, or emotion about something that has already happened: 'I’m glad you’ve come,' 'I doubt they’ve finished,' 'It’s possible she’s left.' Spanish captures this exact feeling with the **present perfect subjunctive**—a combination of *haber* in the present subjunctive (*haya, hayas, haya, hayamos, hayan*) plus a past participle. English does this through tone and context; Spanish does it by blending two layers of time—uncertainty about what’s already done."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ Structure:**\nFormula: *haber (present subjunctive) + past participle.*\n| Subject | Haber (subjunctive) | Example (comer) |\n|----------|----------------------|------------------|\n| yo | haya | haya comido |\n| tú | hayas | hayas comido |\n| él/ella/usted | haya | haya comido |\n| nosotros | hayamos | hayamos comido |\n| vosotros | hayáis | hayáis comido |\n| ellos/ustedes | hayan | hayan comido |\n\n**2️⃣ Function:**\nUsed when the main clause expresses emotion, doubt, uncertainty, or influence about something **that has already occurred.**\n\n- *Me alegra que hayas venido.* (I’m glad you’ve come.)\n- *Dudo que lo hayan visto.* (I doubt they’ve seen it.)\n- *Es posible que haya llegado tarde.* (It’s possible he’s arrived late.)\n\n**3️⃣ Tense relationship:**\n| Main Verb | Time Sense | Subordinate Verb |\n|------------|-------------|------------------|\n| Present / Future | Emotion or doubt about a completed action | Present Perfect Subjunctive |\n| Past / Conditional | Emotion or doubt about a past action | Pluperfect Subjunctive |\n\n**4️⃣ Comparison with indicative:**\nIf the speaker believes the event actually happened → **indicative**: *Creo que ha llegado.* (I believe he’s arrived.)  \nIf they doubt, feel, or react → **subjunctive**: *Dudo que haya llegado.* (I doubt he’s arrived.)\n\n**5️⃣ Common triggers:**\n*me alegra que, dudo que, es posible que, no creo que, ojalá que, temo que, lamento que.*  \nThese phrases all connect emotion or uncertainty with completed reality—the essence of this tense."
    },
