{
  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B2_177_passive_voice",
  "title": "B2.177 Passive Voice — Perspective Shift",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we use the passive voice to shift focus from who did something to what was done: 'The book was written by her,' 'The house was built in 1920.' Spanish does the same, using **ser + past participle**, but it feels more formal and deliberate. English uses the passive naturally in everyday speech; Spanish uses it when the **action itself** matters more than the doer. English does this with word order; Spanish does it by flipping the sentence’s light—from subject to event."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ Structure:**\nFormula: *ser (in the appropriate tense) + past participle (+ por + agent).*  \n- *El libro fue escrito por García Márquez.* (The book was written by García Márquez.)\n- *La casa será construida el próximo año.* (The house will be built next year.)\n\n**2️⃣ Verb Agreement:**\nThe **past participle agrees in gender and number** with the subject, not the doer:\n- *Los cuadros fueron pintados por Picasso.* (The paintings were painted by Picasso.)\n- *Las cartas fueron enviadas ayer.* (The letters were sent yesterday.)\n\n**3️⃣ Time Shifts:**\nChange *ser* to reflect when the action happened:\n| Time | Ser Form | Example |\n|------|-----------|----------|\n| Present | es/son | *El trabajo es hecho por Ana.* |\n| Past (preterite) | fue/fueron | *El trabajo fue hecho por Ana.* |\n| Future | será/serán | *El trabajo será hecho por Ana.* |\n| Conditional | sería/serían | *El trabajo sería hecho por Ana.* |\n\n**4️⃣ Passive vs. Active:**\n| Focus | Structure | Example |\n|--------|------------|----------|\n| Active | subject → action → object | *Ana escribió el libro.* |\n| Passive | object → action → agent | *El libro fue escrito por Ana.* |\n\n**5️⃣ When not to use it:**\nSpanish often prefers **se passives** or **impersonal forms** in casual speech.\n- *Se venden casas.* (Houses are sold.)\n- *Se dice que es verdad.* (It is said that it’s true.)\n→ More natural than *Las casas son vendidas* in everyday conversation.\n\n**6️⃣ Summary:**\nUse the *ser* passive when formality, process, or authorship matters—when you want to highlight the action’s gravity rather than its actor."
    },
