{
  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B2_178_active_vs_passive_restatement",
  "title": "B2.178 Active vs. Passive Restatement — The Grammar of Focus",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we can say the same idea two ways: 'The artist painted the mural' (active) or 'The mural was painted by the artist' (passive). Both describe the same event, but they change what we emphasize—the doer or the action. Spanish follows the same principle with **active and passive structures**, yet uses them more deliberately. English shifts focus by word order; Spanish does it by grammar and rhythm, choosing between energy (active) and elegance (passive)."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ Active voice — subject acts:**\nFormula: *subject + verb + object.*\n- *El chef preparó la cena.* (The chef prepared dinner.)\nActive voice centers the **agent**—who performs the action. It’s direct, vivid, and used in everyday speech.\n\n**2️⃣ Passive voice — subject receives action:**\nFormula: *ser + past participle (+ por + agent).* \n- *La cena fue preparada por el chef.* (Dinner was prepared by the chef.)\nHere, the focus shifts to **the object or result.** The doer becomes secondary or optional.\n\n**3️⃣ Se passive — Spanish’s natural restatement:**\nSpanish prefers *se* to *ser* when the actor isn’t important:\n- *Se preparó la cena.* (Dinner was prepared.)\n- *Se vendieron todas las entradas.* (All the tickets were sold.)\nThis form sounds smoother and is more common than *fue preparada* in conversation.\n\n**4️⃣ Choosing focus intentionally:**\n| Goal | Preferred Form | Example |\n|------|----------------|----------|\n| Emphasize the doer | Active | *Los niños rompieron la ventana.* (The kids broke the window.) |\n| Emphasize the result | Passive | *La ventana fue rota por los niños.* (The window was broken by the kids.) |\n| Hide or generalize the doer | Se passive | *Se rompió la ventana.* (The window broke / was broken.) |\n\n**5️⃣ Common mistake:**\nAvoid overusing the *ser* passive—it can sound overly formal or stiff in everyday Spanish. Instead, use *se* or simply restructure actively: *Los ingenieros construyeron el puente* is cleaner than *El puente fue construido por los ingenieros.*"
    },
