  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B2_180_adjective_placement",
  "title": "B2.180 Adjective Placement — Logic of Meaning and Emotion",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, adjectives almost always come before nouns: 'a red car,' 'a small house,' 'a kind person.' Spanish can do both—adjectives can appear **before or after** the noun—but the choice changes meaning. When the adjective comes **after**, it describes; when it comes **before**, it interprets or emphasizes. English fixes word order; Spanish lets word order reveal attitude, emotion, or focus. Grammar becomes tone, shaping not just what you say, but how you feel about it."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ Basic rule:**\nBy default, Spanish places adjectives **after** the noun.\n- *Un coche rojo* (a red car) → literal description.\n- *Una casa pequeña* (a small house) → objective size.\nWhen the adjective moves **before** the noun, the meaning becomes **subjective or poetic**.\n- *Una pequeña casa* (a lovely little home) → emotional or stylistic tone.\n\n**2️⃣ Position determines meaning:**\n| Adjective | After noun (literal) | Before noun (figurative/emotional) |\n|------------|---------------------|------------------------------------|\n| grande | *un edificio grande* (a big building) | *un gran hombre* (a great man) |\n| viejo | *un amigo viejo* (an old friend, aged) | *un viejo amigo* (a long-time friend) |\n| pobre | *una mujer pobre* (a poor woman, without money) | *una pobre mujer* (a pitiful woman) |\n| cierto | *un hecho cierto* (a true fact) | *una cierta idea* (a certain idea) |\n\n**3️⃣ When order doesn’t change meaning:**\nSome adjectives are neutral in position: *nueva casa / casa nueva* both mean 'new house,' though *nueva casa* can sound more personal or nuanced.\n\n**4️⃣ Multiple adjectives:**\nWhen using two or more adjectives, Spanish orders them logically: value or opinion → size → shape → color → origin → material → purpose.\n- *una elegante mesa redonda de madera española* (an elegant round table made of Spanish wood).\n\n**5️⃣ Emotional shortcut:**\nBefore = subjective, evaluative, emotional.\nAfter = factual, descriptive, neutral.\nSpanish uses position like tone of voice—grammar as inflection."
