  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we use words like 'all,' 'some,' 'none,' and 'a lot' to describe quantity: 'All people,' 'some water,' 'no time.' Spanish uses **quantifiers** too—**todo, algún, ningún, mucho, poco, varios, demasiado**—but they follow strict agreement rules for gender and number. English uses fixed words for any noun; Spanish adjusts each one, shaping even quantity into agreement. English does this with static words; Spanish does it by letting grammar count, feel, and specify every amount precisely."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ Core concept:**\nQuantifiers express **how much** or **how many**—covering both countable (things) and uncountable (substances or ideas) nouns.\n\n**2️⃣ Agreement rules:**\nQuantifiers must match the **gender and number** of the noun they describe.\n| Quantifier | Masculine Singular | Feminine Singular | Masculine Plural | Feminine Plural |\n|-------------|-------------------|-------------------|------------------|------------------|\n| all | todo | toda | todos | todas |\n| some | algún | alguna | algunos | algunas |\n| none | ningún | ninguna | — | — |\n| many/much | mucho | mucha | muchos | muchas |\n| little/few | poco | poca | pocos | pocas |\n| several | varios | varias | — | — |\n| too much/many | demasiado | demasiada | demasiados | demasiadas |\n\n**3️⃣ Placement:**\nQuantifiers typically **precede** the noun: *muchos libros, poca agua, toda la gente.* But *todo* can also come after to emphasize inclusion: *la vida toda* (life itself, poetic).\n\n**4️⃣ Special cases:**\n- *Alguno / ninguno* drop the final -o before a masculine singular noun: *algún libro, ningún problema.*\n- *Todo* with definite articles can mean 'the whole': *todo el día* (the whole day).\n- *Todo + de* shows range or extent: *todo de flores* (full of flowers).\n\n**5️⃣ Common contrasts:**\n| Concept | Spanish | Example |\n|----------|----------|----------|\n| all | todo/toda/todos/todas | *Todos los estudiantes aprobaron.* (All the students passed.) |\n| some | algún/alguna/algunos/algunas | *¿Tienes alguna idea?* (Do you have any idea?) |\n| none | ningún/ninguna | *No tengo ningún problema.* (I don’t have any problem.) |\n| much / many | mucho/muchos | *Hay muchas razones.* (There are many reasons.) |\n| little / few | poco/pocos | *Queda poco tiempo.* (There’s little time left.) |\n\n**6️⃣ Shortcut memory rule:**\n- Use *todo* for inclusion, *mucho* for intensity, *poco* for scarcity, *algún* for possibility, *ningún* for denial. Spanish makes even counting poetic—each amount reveals attitude, not just math."
