{
  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B2_184_sequence_of_moods",
  "title": "B2.184 Sequence of Moods — Grammar of Dependency",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we change verb tense naturally to match context: 'I know he is coming,' 'I knew he was coming.' Spanish does this too—but it also aligns **mood** between clauses. When one verb expresses emotion, doubt, or influence, the next verb shifts its mood to match. This is called **sequence of moods**—the rule that keeps verbs emotionally and logically in tune. English manages this through context and auxiliary verbs; Spanish does it with elegant grammar, harmonizing feeling and time across the sentence."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ The core idea:**\nWhen the main clause triggers the **subjunctive**, the tense of the second verb depends on the time relationship between both actions.\n\n**2️⃣ Step 1 — Identify the main clause’s tense.**\nIf the main verb is in the **present or future**, use **present** or **present perfect subjunctive** in the subordinate clause.\n- *Espero que llegues temprano.* (I hope you arrive early.)\n- *Me alegra que hayas venido.* (I’m glad you’ve come.)\n\nIf the main verb is in the **past (imperfect, preterite, conditional)**, use **imperfect** or **pluperfect subjunctive**.\n- *Esperaba que llegaras temprano.* (I hoped you would arrive early.)\n- *Me alegró que hubieras venido.* (I was glad you had come.)\n\n**3️⃣ Step 2 — Match time and mood:**\n| Main clause (mood/time) | Subordinate clause (mood/time) | Example |\n|--------------------------|--------------------------------|----------|\n| Present / Future | Present Subjunctive | *Espero que venga.* (I hope he comes.) |\n| Present / Future | Present Perfect Subjunctive | *Dudo que haya llegado.* (I doubt he’s arrived.) |\n| Past / Conditional | Imperfect Subjunctive | *Esperaba que viniera.* (I hoped he would come.) |\n| Past / Conditional | Pluperfect Subjunctive | *Esperaba que hubiera llegado.* (I hoped he had arrived.) |\n\n**4️⃣ Step 3 — Remember the emotional link:**\nSequence of moods depends not on strict time, but **relationship**. The two verbs belong to the same emotional or logical chain—when one bends to feeling, the other follows in harmony.\n\n**5️⃣ Tip:**\nIf both verbs belong to the same “emotional moment,” they move together. Spanish keeps clauses synchronized like dancers moving to one rhythm."
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "This system descends from Latin’s mood harmony, which synchronized verb moods across dependent clauses to preserve consistency in meaning and emotion.",
      "story": "The sequence of moods is Spanish’s way of keeping sentences emotionally honest. Every clause reacts to its partner—if the first feels, hopes, or doubts, the second must join in that uncertainty. Grammar becomes empathy: each verb aware of the other’s mood.\n\nThis rule reflects something deeper about the Spanish mind. The language resists emotional contradiction—it doesn’t let one part of a sentence live in certainty while the other trembles in doubt. *Esperaba que llegaras* isn’t just logic—it’s alignment between expectation and the reality of waiting. Both verbs lean into each other like mirrors.\n\nIn daily life, this sequence adds musical balance. *Me alegra que estés bien* sounds whole; *me alegró que estuvieras bien* closes like a sigh. Writers use this harmony to make prose flow like thought—each verb carefully tuned to the time and feeling of the moment. The sequence of moods keeps language coherent, not just in meaning, but in emotion.",
      "wrap_line": "Spanish coordinates grammar the way people coordinate trust—each verb listens to the other, matching tone and time so the sentence stays whole."
    },
