  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B2_185_imperative_mood_advanced",
  "title": "B2.185 Imperative Mood (Advanced) — Commands and Tone",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, giving a command is simple: 'Come here,' 'Be quiet,' 'Let’s go.' Spanish also uses the **imperative mood** for orders, requests, and advice—but it changes form depending on who you’re speaking to and how formal you are. *Ven aquí, venga aquí, vengan aquí* all mean 'come here,' but each carries a different tone. English changes politeness with voice; Spanish does it through grammar, shaping tone directly into the verb."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ The forms:**\nSpanish imperatives depend on **who** is being addressed. Only the **affirmative commands** use unique forms; **negative commands** borrow from the subjunctive.\n\n| Person | Affirmative | Negative |\n|---------|--------------|-----------|\n| tú | *habla, come, vive* | *no hables, no comas, no vivas* |\n| usted | *hable, coma, viva* | *no hable, no coma, no viva* |\n| vosotros | *hablad, comed, vivid* | *no habléis, no comáis, no viváis* |\n| ustedes | *hablen, coman, vivan* | *no hablen, no coman, no vivan* |\n| nosotros | *hablemos, comamos, vivamos* | *no hablemos, no comamos, no vivamos* |\n\n**2️⃣ Irregulars you must know:**\n| Verb | Tú (affirmative) | Usted / Ustedes | Negative Tú |\n|------|------------------|----------------|--------------|\n| decir | di | diga / digan | no digas |\n| hacer | haz | haga / hagan | no hagas |\n| ir | ve | vaya / vayan | no vayas |\n| poner | pon | ponga / pongan | no pongas |\n| salir | sal | salga / salgan | no salgas |\n| ser | sé | sea / sean | no seas |\n| tener | ten | tenga / tengan | no tengas |\n| venir | ven | venga / vengan | no vengas |\n\n**3️⃣ Pronoun placement:**\n- Affirmative → attach pronouns: *Dímelo* (tell it to me), *Levántate* (get up).\n- Negative → place pronouns before: *No me lo digas* (don’t tell it to me).\n\n**4️⃣ Tone and intention:**\nThe imperative is not just for orders—it can express affection (*ven conmigo*), encouragement (*sigue intentando*), or urgency (*¡corre!*). Spanish commands carry mood as much as action, their softness or sharpness defined by formality and form.\n\n**5️⃣ Tip:**\nTo sound natural, match tone to closeness: *hazlo* (casual, familiar), *hágalo* (respectful), *hacedlo* (Spain, plural informal), *háganlo* (Latin America, plural formal)."
