  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we report commands with phrases like 'He told me to come,' 'She asked them not to go.' We shift the command into a softer form using 'to' or 'not to.' Spanish does the same but replaces the direct command with a **subjunctive clause** after verbs of telling or requesting. *Me dijo que viniera, les pidió que no fueran.* English builds politeness with structure; Spanish transforms authority into mood—grammar that balances direction and distance."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ Core idea:**\nReported (indirect) commands express orders, requests, or suggestions **without quoting directly.** Spanish uses verbs of influence—*decir, pedir, ordenar, aconsejar, mandar, rogar, permitir*—followed by *que + subjunctive.*\n\n**2️⃣ Structure:**\nFormula: *main verb (of command) + que + verb (subjunctive).*  \n- *Me dijo que estudiara.* (He told me to study.)\n- *Nos pidió que llegáramos temprano.* (She asked us to arrive early.)\n- *Te ordeno que lo hagas.* (I order you to do it.)\n\n**3️⃣ Affirmative vs. Negative:**\n- *Me dijo que lo hiciera.* (He told me to do it.)\n- *Me dijo que no lo hiciera.* (He told me not to do it.)\nBoth use the **imperfect subjunctive** because the reporting verb is past.\n\n**4️⃣ Present vs. Past sequence:**\n| Main Clause | Subordinate Verb | Example |\n|--------------|------------------|----------|\n| Present | Present Subjunctive | *Le digo que estudie.* (I tell him to study.) |\n| Past | Imperfect Subjunctive | *Le dije que estudiara.* (I told him to study.) |\n| Conditional | Imperfect Subjunctive | *Le diría que estudiara.* (I’d tell him to study.) |\n\n**5️⃣ Common reporting verbs and meanings:**\n| Verb | English meaning | Example |\n|------|------------------|----------|\n| decir | to tell | *Dijo que vinieras.* |\n| pedir | to ask | *Pidió que esperáramos.* |\n| mandar / ordenar | to order | *Ordenó que se fueran.* |\n| rogar / suplicar | to beg | *Rogó que la perdonaran.* |\n| permitir / prohibir | to allow / forbid | *Prohibieron que entráramos.* |\n\n**6️⃣ Tip:**\nDirect command → *Hazlo.*  \nReported command → *Me dijo que lo hiciera.*  \nSpanish softens direct speech into harmony—letting grammar convey both message and respect."
