{
  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B2_188_conditional_sentences_mixed",
  "title": "B2.188 Conditional Sentences (Mixed) — Grammar of Imagination",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we say 'If it rains, I’ll stay home,' 'If I studied, I’d pass,' 'If I had known, I would’ve gone.' Each version shifts time and possibility. Spanish follows the same logic but expresses it more precisely through verb forms. **Si + indicative, subjunctive, or pluperfect subjunctive** combine to measure reality, imagination, and regret. English manages this with 'will,' 'would,' and 'would have'; Spanish builds it into the verbs themselves, turning logic into music."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ The Three Basic Types (Review):**\n| Type | Structure | Meaning | Example |\n|------|------------|----------|----------|\n| Type 1 – Real | *Si + present → future / present* | Likely situation | *Si llueve, me quedo en casa.* (If it rains, I stay home.) |\n| Type 2 – Unreal (present/future) | *Si + imperfect subjunctive → conditional* | Hypothetical or unlikely | *Si tuviera dinero, viajaría más.* (If I had money, I’d travel more.) |\n| Type 3 – Impossible (past) | *Si + pluperfect subjunctive → conditional perfect* | Regret / impossible past | *Si hubiera estudiado, habría aprobado.* (If I had studied, I’d have passed.) |\n\n**2️⃣ Mixed conditionals (crossing time):**\nThese mix past and present to express **how a past condition affects the present**, or vice versa.\n\n| Type | Structure | Meaning | Example |\n|------|------------|----------|----------|\n| Past → Present | *Si hubiera estudiado, tendría un mejor trabajo.* | If I had studied (then), I’d have a better job (now). |\n| Present → Past | *Si fuera más valiente, habría confesado la verdad.* | If I were braver (now), I would have confessed (then). |\n\n**3️⃣ Key idea:**\nThe Spanish conditional chain works like a timeline of cause and imagination. The *si* clause marks the condition; the other clause reveals the imagined result. Both sides mirror time through mood.\n\n**4️⃣ Common variations:**\n- *Aunque* (even if): *Aunque tuviera tiempo, no iría.* (Even if I had time, I wouldn’t go.)\n- *Como si* (as if): *Habla como si lo supiera todo.* (He talks as if he knew everything.)\n\n**5️⃣ Quick diagnostic:**\nAsk yourself two questions:\n1. Is the condition real, unreal, or impossible?\n2. Is the consequence present, future, or past?\nSpanish will always provide the right pair of tenses to fit your answer."
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "From Latin conditional and subjunctive pairings, Spanish perfected a system of balance between reality and desire, using mood to measure distance from fact.",
      "story": "Conditional sentences are where Spanish reveals its philosophical heart. Every *si* clause carries a quiet reflection on possibility. The indicative deals with certainty; the subjunctive with imagination. To say *si tuviera alas, volaría* isn’t simply hypothetical—it’s an act of dreaming within grammar.\n\nThese patterns also capture regret and hope with precision. *Si hubiera sabido, no habría ido* isn’t just sorrow; it’s understanding. The pluperfect subjunctive honors time’s order while admitting human error. Spanish doesn’t run from what can’t be changed—it narrates it elegantly.\n\nMixed conditionals show life’s paradoxes. We live in the present but think about the past; we regret the past while wishing it changed the present. *Si hubiera nacido en otro lugar, hablaría diferente.* (If I had been born elsewhere, I’d speak differently.) Grammar becomes introspection—a structure that holds longing without breaking reason.\n\nEach tense pairing tells a story of awareness: of how people imagine, wish, and reconcile with what didn’t happen.",
      "wrap_line": "Conditional sentences in Spanish make logic emotional—grammar that allows the mind to wonder and the heart to answer, all within a single 'si.'"
    },
    {
      "phase": "context_scene",
      "npc": "teacher",
      "es": "[locked]",
      "you": "[locked]"
    },
