  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B2_189_subjunctive_chain",
  "title": "B2.189 The Subjunctive Chain — When One Verb Triggers Another",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, verbs usually stand on their own: 'I hope you come,' 'I want her to call,' 'I doubt he knows.' Spanish links these ideas more tightly. When one verb expresses **emotion, desire, doubt, or necessity**, it pulls the next verb into the **subjunctive mood**—a grammatical ripple effect. English signals connection through meaning; Spanish shows it through structure, letting verbs echo each other’s mood until the entire sentence feels emotionally in sync."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ The concept:**\nWhen a verb of emotion, will, or doubt appears in the main clause, the verb in the subordinate clause must follow in the **subjunctive**, forming a chain of dependency.\n\nFormula: *Main verb (indicative) + que + subordinate verb (subjunctive).*  \n- *Espero que vengas.* (I hope you come.)\n- *Dudo que sea verdad.* (I doubt it’s true.)\n- *Quiero que me llames.* (I want you to call me.)\n\n**2️⃣ The triggers:**\nVerbs that cause subjunctive chains belong to four main families:\n| Category | Common Triggers | Example |\n|-----------|----------------|----------|\n| Emotion | *alegrarse de, temer, sentir* | *Me alegra que estés aquí.* |\n| Will / Desire | *querer, esperar, pedir, exigir* | *Espero que tengas suerte.* |\n| Doubt / Denial | *dudar, no creer, negar* | *No creo que funcione.* |\n| Influence | *aconsejar, permitir, prohibir* | *Te aconsejo que estudies más.* |\n\n**3️⃣ Sequence of moods (time alignment):**\n| Main Verb Time | Subordinate Verb | Example |\n|-----------------|------------------|----------|\n| Present / Future | Present Subjunctive | *Espero que vengas.* |\n| Past / Conditional | Imperfect Subjunctive | *Esperaba que vinieras.* |\n| Past (referring to earlier action) | Pluperfect Subjunctive | *Esperaba que hubieras venido.* |\n\n**4️⃣ Chain reactions in longer sentences:**\nA subjunctive can trigger another when clauses stack:\n- *Dudo que ella piense que tú estés mintiendo.* (I doubt she thinks you’re lying.)\n- *Quiero que me digas que te alegra que lo haya hecho.* (I want you to tell me you’re glad I did it.)\nEach verb follows the previous one’s emotional or logical tone.\n\n**5️⃣ Quick tip:**\nWhen one clause carries uncertainty or desire, all verbs downstream adjust. Spanish makes logic emotional—one verb’s feeling controls the next verb’s fate."
