  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, verbs can sometimes act like nouns: 'Swimming is fun,' 'Reading helps me relax,' 'Eating vegetables is good for you.' Spanish does the same with the **infinitive**, but even more freely. *Nadar es divertido, leer me relaja, comer verduras es sano.* While English often adds '-ing' to create this effect, Spanish simply uses the verb’s basic form. English changes the word; Spanish changes the way it’s seen—turning an action into an idea without altering its shape."
