  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B2_191_gerund_as_connection",
  "title": "B2.191 The Gerund as Connection — Action in Continuity",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we use '-ing' forms to connect actions or show ongoing activity: 'I’m running,' 'She came singing,' 'They left laughing.' Spanish does this with the **gerund**—verbs ending in *-ando* or *-iendo* that link movement, sequence, or cause. *Estoy corriendo, vino cantando, salieron riendo.* English uses a helper verb like 'be' or a comma; Spanish fuses the motion directly into the verb. English separates action with words; Spanish lets one action flow into the next."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ Structure:**\nForm the **gerundio** by replacing the verb ending with *-ando* (for -ar) or *-iendo* (for -er/-ir):\n- *hablar → hablando* (speaking)\n- *comer → comiendo* (eating)\n- *vivir → viviendo* (living)\n\n**2️⃣ Core uses:**\n| Function | Description | Example |\n|-----------|--------------|----------|\n| Progressive | ongoing action | *Estoy estudiando español.* (I’m studying Spanish.) |\n| Simultaneous actions | two things happening together | *Camina escuchando música.* (He walks while listening to music.) |\n| Cause or manner | explains how or why | *Ganó sonriendo.* (He won by smiling.) |\n| Sequence | shows result or follow-up | *Salió corriendo.* (He ran out / left running.) |\n\n**3️⃣ Progressive tenses:**\nThe **gerund** works with *estar* to express continuous action:\n| Time | Structure | Example |\n|------|------------|----------|\n| Present | *estar (present) + gerund* | *Estoy leyendo.* (I’m reading.) |\n| Past | *estar (imperfect) + gerund* | *Estaba leyendo.* (I was reading.) |\n| Future | *estar (future) + gerund* | *Estaré leyendo.* (I’ll be reading.) |\n\n**4️⃣ Rules and restrictions:**\n- The gerund never functions as a noun (*El fumar* = correct, *Fumando* = incorrect for 'smoking').\n- It cannot modify nouns directly (*una mujer cantando* is fine in speech but not as a formal adjective).\n- It only refers to **simultaneous or related** actions—not sequential facts.\n  - ❌ *Llegó, comiendo después.* → ✅ *Llegó y comió después.*\n\n**5️⃣ Common expressions:**\n- *Andando el tiempo* (as time goes by)\n- *Siguiendo las reglas* (following the rules)\n- *Pensándolo bien* (on second thought)\n\nSpanish uses the gerund to thread ideas together, turning verbs into bridges rather than walls."
