  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B2_194_word_order_variations",
  "title": "B2.194 Word Order Variations — Rhythm and Emphasis",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, word order rarely changes. We rely on structure for meaning: subject, verb, object—'The dog chased the cat.' Spanish, however, allows flexibility. *El perro persiguió al gato*, *Al gato lo persiguió el perro*, even *Persiguió al gato el perro*—all are correct, each with a different focus. English builds meaning through order; Spanish builds it through rhythm and emphasis, bending structure to match emotion, intention, or surprise."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ Default pattern:**\nThe neutral Spanish sentence order follows **SVO (subject + verb + object)**, just like English.\n- *El niño come manzanas.* (The boy eats apples.)\n\nBut Spanish is flexible because the **verb endings** already mark who does the action. *Come manzanas* (He/She eats apples) is perfectly clear even without *el niño.* This freedom lets Spanish reorder words for emphasis or style.\n\n**2️⃣ Common variations and their effect:**\n| Order | Example | Emphasis |\n|--------|----------|-----------|\n| SVO | *El perro mordió al hombre.* | Neutral statement. |\n| VSO | *Mordió el perro al hombre.* | Dramatic / literary tone, emphasizes the action. |\n| OVS | *Al hombre lo mordió el perro.* | Emphasizes the object—'It was the man who was bitten.' |\n| OSV | *Al hombre el perro mordió.* | Poetic or formal rhythm, often used in storytelling. |\n\n**3️⃣ Inversion for questions:**\nSpanish flips subject and verb to form questions, just like English:\n- *¿Comes tú manzanas?* (Do you eat apples?)\n- *¿Dónde está María?* (Where is María?)\nPronouns often stay attached or placed before verbs, preserving clarity: *¿Qué te dijo?* (What did he tell you?)\n\n**4️⃣ Fronting for emphasis:**\nSpanish allows words to be moved to the front for focus.\n- *A mí me gusta el café.* (As for me, I like coffee.)\n- *En casa estoy mejor.* (At home, I feel better.)\n- *Lo hice yo.* (I did it.)\n\n**5️⃣ Key note:**\nWord order in Spanish is less about grammar and more about **intonation and attention.** The rules stay consistent, but the spotlight shifts. The placement tells you what the speaker finds most important."
