  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we show cause and effect with words like 'because,' 'since,' or 'so': 'I left because it was late,' 'Since it rained, we stayed home,' 'He worked hard, so he succeeded.' Spanish does the same with **porque, ya que, como, así que, por eso** and more. The difference is tone and placement. English explains logically; Spanish does it musically, choosing each connector for rhythm and nuance. English builds reason like an argument; Spanish delivers it like a story—cause flowing naturally into effect."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ Cause clauses — answering why:**\nThese explain reasons or motives for an action. They’re usually introduced by *porque, ya que, como,* or *puesto que.*\n\n| Connector | Meaning | Example |\n|------------|----------|----------|\n| porque | because | *No salí porque llovía.* (I didn’t go out because it was raining.) |\n| ya que | since / seeing that | *Ya que estás aquí, ayúdame.* (Since you’re here, help me.) |\n| como | as / since | *Como no vino, me fui.* (As he didn’t come, I left.) |\n| puesto que | given that | *Puesto que no hay tiempo, terminemos rápido.* (Given that there’s no time, let’s finish quickly.) |\n\n**Placement rule:**\nWhen *como* or *puesto que* starts a sentence, they carry a softer, explanatory tone. *Porque* usually appears after the main clause.\n- *No fui porque estaba cansado.*\n- *Como estaba cansado, no fui.*\n\n**2️⃣ Effect clauses — answering what happened as a result:**\nThese explain consequences, introduced by *así que, por eso, de modo que, por lo tanto, por consiguiente.*\n\n| Connector | Meaning | Example |\n|------------|----------|----------|\n| así que | so / therefore | *Llovía, así que no salimos.* (It was raining, so we didn’t go out.) |\n| por eso | that’s why | *No estudió, por eso reprobó.* (He didn’t study, that’s why he failed.) |\n| de modo que | so that / in such a way that | *Trabajó mucho, de modo que logró el ascenso.* |\n| por lo tanto | therefore | *Estaba enfermo, por lo tanto no vino.* |\n| por consiguiente | consequently | *No pagó, por consiguiente perdió el servicio.* |\n\n**3️⃣ Grammar note:**\nUnlike English, Spanish doesn’t use commas to separate *porque* from its clause and prefers simpler punctuation. The order can shift for tone—*porque* explains, *así que* resolves. Cause feels internal; effect looks forward."
