      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ The core structures:**\n| English | Spanish | When to Use |\n|----------|----------|--------------|\n| in order to / to | *para + infinitive* | when both clauses share the same subject |\n| so that | *para que + subjunctive* | when each clause has a different subject |\n\n**Examples:**\n- *Salgo temprano para descansar.* (I leave early **to rest.**) → same subject.\n- *Salgo temprano para que tú descanses.* (I leave early **so that you rest.**) → different subjects.\n\n**2️⃣ The mechanics:**\n- *Para + infinitive* functions like a prepositional phrase, compact and direct.\n- *Para que + subjunctive* introduces a subordinate clause, requiring mood change because the second action depends on the first.\n\n**3️⃣ Common verbs and phrases of purpose:**\n| Verb / Phrase | Example |\n|----------------|----------|\n| trabajar para | *Trabajo para ganar dinero.* (I work to earn money.) |\n| estudiar para que | *Estudia para que sus padres estén orgullosos.* (He studies so that his parents are proud.) |\n| venir para | *Vine para ayudarte.* (I came to help you.) |\n| decir para que | *Te lo digo para que sepas la verdad.* (I tell you so that you know the truth.) |\n\n**4️⃣ Subtle alternatives:**\nOther connectors add nuance to purpose:\n| Connector | Meaning | Example |\n|------------|----------|----------|\n| a fin de / a fin de que | with the aim of / so that | *A fin de que todo funcione, revisa los cables.* |\n| con el propósito de / que | with the purpose of | *Con el propósito de mejorar, practica cada día.* |\n| para evitar que | to prevent that | *Sal temprano para evitar que lleguen tarde.* |\n\n**5️⃣ Quick trick:**\nAsk: is the purpose something **I** do, or something **someone else** does? Same subject → infinitive; different subjects → subjunctive."
