  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we use words like 'unless,' 'as long as,' or 'provided that' to talk about conditions: 'I’ll go unless it rains,' 'You can come as long as you help.' Spanish does the same, using **conditional connectors** such as *a menos que, con tal (de) que, siempre que, en caso de que.* The difference lies in mood. English shows condition through meaning; Spanish shows it through grammar, switching between the **indicative** for reality and the **subjunctive** for possibility."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ What conditional connectors do:**\nThey join two clauses—one expressing a condition, the other the result. Spanish uses different conjunctions depending on whether the condition is real, imagined, or restrictive.\n\n**2️⃣ Common connectors and their moods:**\n| Connector | Meaning | Mood | Example |\n|------------|----------|------|----------|\n| *si* | if | indicative / subjunctive | *Si vienes, te ayudo.* (If you come, I’ll help you.) / *Si vinieras, te ayudaría.* (If you came, I’d help you.) |\n| *a menos que* | unless | subjunctive | *Iremos, a menos que llueva.* (We’ll go, unless it rains.) |\n| *con tal (de) que* | as long as / provided that | subjunctive | *Puedes salir con tal de que termines la tarea.* (You can go out as long as you finish your homework.) |\n| *siempre que* | provided that / whenever | subjunctive / indicative | *Siempre que estudies, aprobarás.* (Whenever you study, you’ll pass.) |\n| *en caso de que* | in case | subjunctive | *Llévate un paraguas en caso de que llueva.* (Take an umbrella in case it rains.) |\n\n**3️⃣ Subjunctive vs. indicative logic:**\n- **Indicative** → Used when the condition feels likely or factual.\n  - *Si hace sol, saldremos.* (If it’s sunny, we’ll go out.)\n- **Subjunctive** → Used when the condition is uncertain, hypothetical, or preventive.\n  - *En caso de que haya tráfico, sal temprano.* (In case there’s traffic, leave early.)\n\n**4️⃣ Word order and flexibility:**\nConditional connectors can appear at the start or middle of the sentence:\n- *A menos que llueva, iremos al parque.* / *Iremos al parque a menos que llueva.*\n\n**5️⃣ Shortcut rule:**\nIf the connector carries a sense of **uncertainty, restriction, or prevention**, it will almost always require the **subjunctive.**"
