  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B2_199_temporal_connectors",
  "title": "B2.199 Temporal Connectors — Grammar of Time Flow",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, we use words like 'when,' 'as soon as,' 'until,' and 'after' to connect events in time: 'When he arrives, we’ll start,' 'I’ll call you after I finish.' Spanish uses the same logic with **temporal connectors** like *cuando, en cuanto, hasta que, después de que,* but with one major twist—the **mood changes**. English shows timing through sequence; Spanish shows it through **certainty versus possibility**, using the subjunctive for what hasn’t happened yet and the indicative for what has."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ Purpose:**\nTemporal connectors join two actions and clarify **when** one happens in relation to the other—before, after, during, or until.\n\n**2️⃣ Common temporal connectors:**\n| Connector | Meaning | Mood | Example |\n|------------|----------|------|----------|\n| cuando | when | indicative (past/habitual) / subjunctive (future) | *Cuando llegue, te llamo.* (When he arrives, I’ll call you.) |\n| en cuanto | as soon as | indicative / subjunctive | *En cuanto termines, salimos.* (As soon as you finish, we’ll leave.) |\n| hasta que | until | indicative / subjunctive | *No me iré hasta que vengas.* (I won’t leave until you come.) |\n| antes de que | before | subjunctive only | *Llama antes de que salga.* (Call before he leaves.) |\n| después de que | after | indicative / subjunctive | *Te veré después de que regreses.* (I’ll see you after you return.) |\n| mientras | while / as long as | indicative / subjunctive | *Mientras estudies, mejorarás.* (As long as you study, you’ll improve.) |\n\n**3️⃣ Mood rule (the heart of the concept):**\n- **Indicative:** when the time reference is **known, habitual, or completed.**\n  - *Siempre me llama cuando llega.* (He always calls when he arrives.)\n- **Subjunctive:** when the time reference is **pending, uncertain, or unreal.**\n  - *Me llamará cuando llegue.* (He will call when he arrives.)\n\n**4️⃣ Special connectors with prepositions:**\n| Preposition + infinitive | Meaning | Example |\n|---------------------------|----------|----------|\n| antes de + infinitive | before doing | *Antes de salir, revisa el correo.* |\n| después de + infinitive | after doing | *Después de comer, descansa un poco.* |\n| al + infinitive | upon doing | *Al llegar, te aviso.* |\n\n**5️⃣ Quick tip:**\nIf the event has **already happened** → indicative.  \nIf it **hasn’t yet** → subjunctive.  \nSpanish measures time not by clocks, but by certainty."
