{
  "id": "mmspanish__lesson_B2_200_conjunction_summary",
  "title": "B2.200 Conjunction Summary — Grammar of Logic",
  "mode": "mix_method",
  "steps": [
    {
      "phase": "english_anchor",
      "line": "In English, conjunctions—words like 'and,' 'but,' 'because,' and 'although'—act as bridges between ideas. They tell us how one thought connects to another. Spanish uses the same logic with **conjunctions** like *y, pero, porque, aunque,* yet it treats these links with more precision. English joins ideas fluidly; Spanish builds meaning by **type of connection**—addition, contrast, cause, purpose, condition, or time. English relies on flow; Spanish relies on structure, making logic sound graceful and exact."
    },
    {
      "phase": "system_logic",
      "line": "**1️⃣ What conjunctions do:**\nConjunctions join two clauses or ideas, showing the relationship between them. Spanish divides them into clear types:\n\n**A. Coordinating Conjunctions** — join **equal ideas.**\n| Type | Conjunction | Example |\n|------|--------------|----------|\n| Addition | *y (and), e (before i/hi)* | *Juan y Ana estudian.* (Juan and Ana study.) |\n| Contrast | *pero (but), sino (but rather)* | *No quiero té, sino café.* (I don’t want tea, but rather coffee.) |\n| Cause/Result | *pues, así que, por lo tanto* | *Estaba cansado, así que se fue.* (He was tired, so he left.) |\n| Choice | *o, u (before o/ho)* | *¿Quieres té u otra cosa?* (Do you want tea or something else?) |\n\n**B. Subordinating Conjunctions** — join **unequal ideas**, where one depends on the other.\n| Function | Conjunction | Example |\n|-----------|-------------|----------|\n| Cause | *porque, ya que, como* | *No fui porque llovía.* (I didn’t go because it was raining.) |\n| Purpose | *para que, a fin de que* | *Vino para que lo ayudara.* (He came so that I’d help him.) |\n| Condition | *si, a menos que, con tal de que* | *Iré si tengo tiempo.* (I’ll go if I have time.) |\n| Time | *cuando, hasta que, en cuanto* | *Te llamo cuando llegue.* (I’ll call when I arrive.) |\n| Contrast / Concession | *aunque, a pesar de que, por más que* | *Aunque llueva, iremos.* (Even if it rains, we’ll go.) |\n\n**2️⃣ Mood connection:**\n- **Indicative** → facts, certainty: *porque llueve* (because it rains).\n- **Subjunctive** → uncertainty, intention, doubt: *para que vengas* (so that you come).\n\n**3️⃣ Linking rules:**\n- Avoid repetition: *y* changes to *e* before words beginning with *i-* or *hi-*, and *o* changes to *u* before *o-* or *ho-*.\n  - *Padre e hijo* (father and son), *siete u ocho* (seven or eight).\n- Commas separate independent clauses when needed: *Llegó tarde, pero explicó por qué.*\n\n**4️⃣ Quick memory trick:**\nIf the second clause depends on the first, it’s a **subordinating conjunction**. If it stands equal, it’s **coordinating.** Spanish grammar literally structures logic into two levels—balance and hierarchy."
    },
    {
      "phase": "meaning_depth",
      "origin": "From Latin connective particles, Spanish developed a clear hierarchy of conjunctions to mirror the logic of speech and the rhythm of storytelling.",
      "story": "In Spanish, conjunctions are the invisible architecture of meaning. Each one carries weight—not just linking words, but defining the relationship between thoughts. *Y* feels smooth, *pero* resists, *aunque* softens, *para que* aspires. The grammar doesn’t just connect ideas—it gives them emotion and direction.\n\nSpanish treats conjunctions as the breath between ideas. In daily conversation, they mirror personality. Someone who says *sin embargo* sounds reflective; someone who says *pero bueno* sounds casual, forgiving. The choice of connector reveals the speaker’s inner rhythm—the logic of their heart as much as their mind.\n\nIn writing, conjunctions create structure and tone. *Y el mundo giraba.* adds motion; *pero el mundo cambió.* adds consequence. Poets use them to control silence as much as connection. The power lies in balance: Spanish grammar reminds us that even logic can sound lyrical when every bridge is placed with care.",
